'''''Verbascum thapsus''''' ({{pronEng|vɝˈbæskəm ˈθæpsəs}}; '''Great Mullein''' or '''Common Mullein''') is a species of [[mullein]] native to [[Europe]], northern [[Africa]] and [[Asia]], and introduced in the [[Americas]] and [[Australia]]. 

It is a hairy [[biennial plant]] that can grow to 2&nbsp;[[metre|m]] or more tall. Its small yellow flowers are densely grouped on the tall stem, which bolts from a large rosette of leaves. It grows in a wide variety of habitats, but prefers well-lit disturbed soils, where it can appear soon after the ground receives light, from long-lived seeds that persist in the [[soil seed bank]]. It is a common weedy plant that spreads by prolifically producing seeds, but rarely becomes aggressively [[invasive species|invasive]] since its seed require open ground to [[germination|germinate]]. It is a very minor problem for most agricultural crops since it is not a very competitive species, being intolerant of shade from other plants and unable to survive tilling. It also hosts many insects, some of which can be harmful to other plants. Although individuals are easy to remove by hand, populations are difficult to eliminate permanently.

It is widely used for herbal remedies with [[emollient]] and [[astringent]] properties. It is especially recommended for coughs and related problems, but also used in [[topical]] applications against a variety of skin problems. The plant was also used to make [[dye]]s and [[torch]]es.

==Description==

[[Image:Starr 040723 0260 verbascum thapsus.jpg|left|thumb|A stemless rosette in [[Hawaii]]]]

''Verbascum thapsus'' is a [[dicotyledon]]ous biennial that produces a [[rosette (botany)|rosette]] of leaves in its first year of growth.<ref name="FlEu">{{cite encyclopedia | last = Ferguson | first = Ian Keith | editor = Tutin, Thomas Gaskell ''et als.'' | encyclopedia = Flora Europaea | title = V. thapsus | year = 1972 | publisher = Cambridge University Press | volume = Volume 3: Diapensiaceae to Myoporaceae | location = Cambridge | id = ISBN 0-521-08489-X | pages = p. 211}}</ref><ref name="blamey">Blamey, M., & Grey-Wilson, C. (1989). ''Flora of Britain and Northern Europe''. Hodder & Stoughton ISBN 0-340-40170-2.</ref> The leaves are large, up to 50 cm long, and are covered with woolly, silvery hairs. The second year plants normally produce a single unbranched stem 1–2&nbsp;m tall, with some plants reportedly having stems reaching up to 3.5&nbsp;m tall.<ref>[http://www.purplesage.org.uk/profiles/mullein.htm Purple Sage Herbs: ''Verbascum thapsus''], retrieved on [[December 29]] [[2006]].</ref> In the east of its range in China, it is however only reported to 1.5 m tall.<ref name="china">{{Cite web|title=Verbascum thapsus|url=http://www.efloras.org/florataxon.aspx?flora_id=2&taxon_id=200021301|work=Flora of China|publisher=eFloras.org|accessdate=2006-11-29}}</ref> The tall pole-like stems end in a dense [[raceme|spike]] of flowers,<ref name="FlEu"/> that can occupy up to half the stem length. All parts of the plants are covered with star-shaped [[trichome]]s.<ref name="china"/><ref name="jepson">{{cite web|last=Wetherwax|first=M.| year=1993|title=Verbascum thapsus L. |url=http://ucjeps.berkeley.edu/cgi-bin/get_JM_treatment.pl?7177,7595,7598 |work=Jepson Manual online|publisher=[[University of California at Berkeley]]|accessdate=2006-12-06}}</ref> Its [[chromosome number]] is 2n&nbsp;=&nbsp;36.<ref name="NWeurope"/>

On flowering plants the leaves are alternately arranged up the stem. The leaves are thick, and [[decurrent]] on the stem, with much variation especially between the upper and lower leaves on the stem, with leaf shape ranging from between [[leaf shape|oblong to oblanceolate]] and ranging in size up to 50&nbsp;cm long and 14&nbsp;cm across (19&nbsp;inches long and 5&nbsp;inches wide).<ref name="huxley">Huxley, A., ed. (1992). ''New RHS Dictionary of Gardening''. Macmillan. ISBN 0-333-47494-5</ref><ref name="remaley"/> They become smaller higher up the stem,<ref name="FlEu"/><ref name="blamey"/> and less strongly decurrent lower down the stem.<ref name="FlEu"/> The flowering stem is solid and 2–2.5&nbsp;cm (nearly an inch) across, and occasionally [[branch]]ed just below the [[inflorescence]],<ref name="blamey"/> usually when damaged.<ref name="Hoshovsky">{{cite web|first=Marc C.|last= Hoshovsky|title=Element Stewardship Abstract for Verbascum thapsus|url=http://tncweeds.ucdavis.edu/esadocs/documnts/verbtha.pdf| month=August |year=2001 |publisher= The Global Invasive Species Initiative|accessdate=2006-11-29}}</ref> After flowering and seed release the stem and fruits usually persist in winter<ref name="illinois"/> after drying into hard, stiff structures topped with densely packed, ovoid shaped, dry seed capsules. The dried stems are most often dark brownish, and often persist standing until the next spring or even into the next summer. The plants produce a shallow [[taproot]].<ref name="remaley"/>

[[Image:Starr 040723 0267 verbascum thapsus.jpg|right|thumb|A closeup of the flowers]]
The flowers are pentamerous with five [[stamen]] that are fused to the petals and a 5-lobed [[calyx tube]] and a 5-petalled [[corolla]], the latter bright yellow and an 1.5–3&nbsp;cm (0.5–1&nbsp;inch) wide. The flowers are almost [[sessile]], with very short [[pedicel (botany)|pedicel]]s (2&nbsp;mm, 0.08&nbsp;in). The five stamens are of two types, with the three upper stamens being shorter, with filaments covered by yellow or whitish hairs, and having smaller [[anther]]s, while the lower two stamens have [[glabrous]] filaments and larger anthers.<ref name="jepson"/>{{ref label|Stamens|A|}} The plant produces small ovoid (6&nbsp;mm, 0.24&nbsp;in) [[capsule (fruit)|capsule]]s that split open by way of two valves, each capsule containing large numbers of minute brown [[seed]]s less than a millimetre (0.04&nbsp;in)<ref name="davis"/> in size, with longitudinal ridges. A white-flowered form ''V. thapsus'' f. ''candicans'' occurs.<ref name="pennel"/> Flowering lasts for up to three months from early to late summer (June to August in northern Europe),<ref name="blamey"/> with flowering starting at the bottom of the spike and progressing irregularly up the spike with each flower open for part of a day with only a few flowers open at the same time produced around the stem.<ref name="illinois"/>

==Distribution and introduction==

''Verbascum thapsus'' has a wide native range including [[Europe]], northern [[Africa]] and [[Asia]], from the [[Azores]] and [[Canary Islands]] east to western [[China]], north to the [[British Isles]], [[Scandinavia]] and [[Siberia]], and south to the [[Himalayas]].<ref name="china"/><ref name="flora">[http://rbg-web2.rbge.org.uk/cgi-bin/nph-readbtree.pl/feout?FAMILY_XREF=&GENUS_XREF=Verbascum&SPECIES_XREF=thapsus Flora Europaea: ''Verbascum thapsus''], retrieved on [[December 29]] [[2006]].</ref><ref name="grin">[http://www.ars-grin.gov/cgi-bin/npgs/html/taxon.pl?41150 Germplasm Resources Information Network: ''Verbascum thapsus''], retrieved on [[December 29]] [[2006]].</ref> In northern Europe, it grows from sea level up to 1,850 m altitude,<ref name="blamey"/> while in China it grows at 1,400-3,200 m altitude.<ref name="china"/>

It has been introduced throughout the temperate world, and is [[naturalisation (biology)|established]] as a [[weed]] in [[Australia]], [[New Zealand]], tropical Asia, [[La Réunion]], [[North America]], [[Hawaii]], [[Chile]], [[Hispaniola]] and [[Argentina]].<ref name = "grin"/><ref>{{Es icon}} {{cite web|title=  Ficha de la Especie Verbascum thapsus|url=http://www.uns.edu.ar/inbiar/ver_especie.asp?especie_id=333|work=Base de Datos sobre Invasiones Biológicas en Argentina|publisher=Universidad Nacional del Sur|accessdate=2006-12-06}}</ref><ref name="ISSG">{{cite web|title=Verbascum thapsus|url=http://www.issg.org/database/species/ecology.asp?si=695|date=[[8 July]] [[2005]]|work=Global Invasive Species Database|publisher=IUCN Invasive Species Specialist Group|accessdate=2006-11-29}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title= Verbascum thapsus |url=http://www.hear.org/Pier/species/verbascum_thapsus.htm| publisher= Hawaiian Ecosystems at Risk project |work= Pacific Island Ecosystems at Risk| date=[[February 19]], [[2007]]|accessdate=2007-05-12}}</ref> It has also been reported in [[Japan]].<ref>{{cite web| title=List of alien species recognized to be established in Japan or found in the Japanese wild (as of October 27, 2004)| url=http://www.env.go.jp/en/nature/as/041110.pdf| Japan: Ministry of Environment| accessdate=2007-05-12}}</ref>

In the United States it was imported very early in the 18th{{ref label|Date_Mitch|C|}} century and cultivated for its medicinal and [[piscicide]] property. By 1818, it had begun spreading so much that [[Amos Eaton]] thought it was a native plant.{{ref label|Eaton|B|}}<ref name="remaley"/><ref name="mitch">{{cite web|last=Mitch|first=Larry W.|title=  Common Mullein&mdash;the Roadside Torch Parade|url=http://wssa.net/Weeds/ID/WorldOfWeeds/mullein.html |work=Intriguing World of Weeds|publisher=Weed Science Society of America|accessdate=2006-12-06}}</ref> In 1839 it was already reported in [[Michigan]] and in 1876, in [[California]].<ref name="remaley">{{cite web|first=Tom|last=Remaley|title=Verbascum thapsus|url=http://www.nps.gov/plants/alien/fact/veth1.htm|year=1998|publisher=Plant Conservation Alliance's Alien Plant Working Group|accessdate=2006-11-29}}</ref> It is now found commonly in all the states.<ref>{{cite web|title=Verbascum thapsus|url=http://plants.usda.gov/java/profile?symbol=VETH| work=PLANTS Database| publisher=[[United States Department of Agriculture|USDA]] [[Natural Resources Conservation Service]]| accessdate=2006-12-06}}</ref> In [[Canada]], it most common in Southern [[Quebec]], [[Ontario]] and [[British Columbia]], and in the [[Maritime Provinces]], with scattered populations in between.<ref name="BoCW"/><ref>[http://www.natureserve.org/explorer/servlet/NatureServe?searchName=verbascum+thapsus]: ''Verbascum thapsus'', retrieved [[December 29]] [[2006]].</ref>

==Taxonomy and nomenclature==
<!-- [[Image:Vthapsus sheet.JPG|thumb|right|The dried type specimen (LINN 242.1) of ''Verbascum thapsus''.]]-->
For the purpose of [[botanical nomenclature]], ''Verbascum thapsus'' was first described by [[Carolus Linnaeus]] in his 1753 ''[[Species Plantarum]]''. The [[specific epithet]] ''thapsus'' had been first used by [[Theophrastus]] (as ''θάψος'', "thapsos")<ref name="carnoy"/> for an unspecified herb from the [[Ancient Greece|Ancient Greek]] settlement of Thapsos, near modern [[Syracuse, Sicily|Syracuse]], [[Sicily]],<ref name="carnoy">{{fr icon}}{{cite book| last=Carnoy| first=A. |title=Dictionnaire étymologique des noms grecs de plantes| year=1959|location=Louvain| publisher= Publications Universitaires| oclc=3284108}}</ref><ref>{{sv icon}} [http://linnaeus.nrm.se/flora/di/scrophularia/verba/verbtha.html Den virtuella Floran: ''Verbascum thapsus''], retrieved on [[December 29]] [[2006]].</ref> though it is often assimilated to the ancient [[Tunisia]]n city of [[Thapsus]].<ref>{{Cite web|last=Charters|first=Michael L.|title=Plant name: T| work= California Plant Names: Latin and Greek Meanings and Derivations| url=http://www.calflora.net/botanicalnames/pageT.html|publisher=Calflora.net| accessdate=2006-12-06}}</ref> Within ''[[Verbascum]]'', it classified under section ''Bothrosperma'' subsect. ''Fasciculata''.<!--reference temporary, details to come from Murbeck (1933)--><ref>{{cite journal|last=Lersten|first=Nels R.| coauthor=John D. Curtis|title=Anatomy and Distribution of Foliar Idioblasts in Scrophularia and Verbascum (Scrophulariaceae)| month=December| year=1997| volume=84|issue=12| pages=1638-1645| doi=10.2307/2446461}}</ref>

At the time, no [[type specimen]] was specified, as the practice only appeared later, in the 19th century. When a lectotype (type selected amongst original material) was designated, it was assigned to specimen 242.1 of Linnaeus' herbarium, the only ''V. thapsus'' specimen. The species had previously been designated as [[type species]] for ''Verbascum''.<ref>{{cite web| title=''Verbascum thapsus''| url=http://www.nhm.ac.uk/jdsml/research-curation/projects/linnaean-typification/detail.dsml?ID=925400| work=Linnaean Plant Name Typification Project| publisher=Natural History Museum| accessdate=2007-05-14}}</ref> European plants exhibit considerable [[phenotype|phenotypical]] variation,<ref name="BoCW"/> which has led to the plant acquiring many [[synonymy|synonyms]] over the years.<ref>{{Cite web| title=''Verbascum thapsus'' synonymy| url=http://www.northernontarioflora.ca/chklst.cfm?speciesid=1004482| publisher=Northern Ontario Plant Database|accessdate=2007-05-14}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web| title=''Verbascum thapsus'': synonyms| url=http://www.plantatlas.usf.edu/synonyms.asp?plantID=1757| work=Atlas of Florida vascular Plants | publisher=Institute for Systematic Botany |accessdate=2007-05-14}}</ref> Introduced American populations show much less variation.<ref name="BoCW"/>

Type specimen(s)
* Lectotype: (LINN-242.1). Designated by L. H. Cramer, in Dassanayake & Fosberg, ''A Revised Handbook to the Flora of Ceylon'' 3: 389 (1981)<ref>{{Cite web| title=''Verbascum thapsus'': citation| url=http://www.plantatlas.usf.edu/details.asp?plantID=1757| work=Atlas of Florida vascular Plants | publisher=Institute for Systematic Botany |accessdate=2007-05-16}}</ref>

===Subspecies and hybrids===

There are three [[subspecies]]:
*''V. thapsus'' subsp. ''thapsus''; type, widespread.
*''V. thapsus'' subsp. ''crassifolium'' (Lam.) Murb.; Mediterranean region and to 2000 metres in southwestern Austria.<ref name=schmeil/> (syn. subsp. ''montanum'' (Scrad.) Bonnier & Layens)
*''V. thapsus'' subsp. ''giganteum'' (Willk.) Nyman; Spain, endemic.
In all subspecies but the type, the lower stamens are also pilose (having scattered straight long soft hairs).<ref>{{es icon}} {{cite web|title=''Verbascum thapsus'' L. subsp. ''montanum'' (Schrad.) Bonnier et layens |url=http://herbarivirtual.uib.es/cas-med/especie/4440.html| publisher=Universitat de les Illes Balears| work=Herbario Virtual del Mediterráneo Occidental| accessdate=2007-05-12}}</ref> In subsp. ''crassifolium'', the hairiness is less dense and often absent from the upper part of the anthers, and lower leaves are hardly decurrent and have longer petioles<ref name=schmeil>{{cite book| last =Schmeil| first =Otto| authorlink =| coauthors =Fitschen, Jost; Seybold, Siegmund| title =Flora von Deutschland, 93. Auflage| publisher =Quelle & Meyer Verlag| date =2006| location =Wiebelsheim| pages =496| url =| doi =| isbn =3-494-01413-2 }}</ref>, whereas in subsp. ''giganteum'', the hairs are densely white tomentose, and lower leaves strongly decurrent. Subsp. ''crassifolium'' also differs from the type in having slightly larger flowers, which measure 15–30 mm wide, whereas in the type they are 12–20 mm in diameter.<ref name=schmeil/> Both subsp. ''giganteum'' and subsp. ''crassifolium'' were originally described as species.<ref name="FlEu"/> Other described subspecies that have not been widely accepted include subsp. ''martinezii'' (Valdés) A.Galán and J.A.V.Orellana (=''V. giganteum'' subsp. ''martinezii'' Valdés), subsp. ''litigiosum'' (=''V. litigiosum'' Samp.)<ref>{{cite journal| last=Galán de Mera| first=Antonio| coauthor=José Alfredo Vicente
Orellana|title=Dos nuevas combinaciones en ''Verbascum'' subsect. ''fasciculata'' Murbeck (Scrophulariaceae) del sudoeste de la Península Ibérica: ''Verbascum thapsus'' subsp. ''litigiosum'' (Samp.), comb. & stat. nov. y ''Verbascum thapsus'' subsp. ''martinezii'' (Valdés), comb. nov.| Anales del Jardín Botánico de Madrid|year=1995|volume=53|issue=2|pages=261-262| url=http://www.rjb.csic.es/pdfs/Anales_53(2)_245_270.pdf| accessdate=2007-05-14}}</ref> and subsp. ''langei''.

{| class="prettytable" style="clear:right;float:right;text-align:center; font-size:90%;width:350px;margin:0 0 0.5em 1em;"
