The plant is also parent to several hybrids (''see table''). Of these, the most common is ''V. × semialbum'' Chaub. (× ''[[Verbascum nigrum|V. nigrum]]'').<ref name="NWeurope"/> All occur in Eurasia,<ref name="NWeurope"/> and three, ''V. × kerneri'' Fritsch, ''V. × pterocaulon'' Franch. and ''V. × thapsi'' L. ([[Synonymy|syn.]] ''V. × spurium'' W.D.J.Koch), have also been reported in North America.<ref name="kartesz"/><ref>{{cite web| url=http://plants.usda.gov/java/profile?symbol=VERBA| title=''Verbascum'' L.| work=PLANTS Profile| publisher=USDA Natural resources Conservation Service| accessdate=2007-03-07}}</ref>

===Common names===

''V. thapsus'' is known by a variety of names. The standard English name used by authorities in its native area is Great Mullein.<ref name =jncc>Joint Nature Conservation Committee: [http://www.jncc.gov.uk/default.aspx?page=3316&SpeciesID=26550&type=species Great Mullein ''Verbascum thapsus'' Linnaeus]</ref><ref name =bsbi>Botanical Society of the British Isles [http://www.bsbi.org.uk/html/database.html Database]</ref><ref name="grieve"/><ref name="elsevier633">{{cite book|last=Watts| first=Donald| title=  Elsevier's Dictionary of Plant Names and their Origin| year=2000| location=Amsterdam| publisher=Elsevier Science| pages=pp.633-634| isbn=0-444-50356-0}}</ref> In North America, "Common mullein" is the usual name.<ref>{{cite book| last=Niering |first=William A. |title=  The Audubon Society field guide to North American wildflowers, eastern region| location=New York| publisher=Knopf| year=1979| isbn=0-394-50432-1|pages=p. 798}}</ref><ref name="Rickett">{{cite encyclopedia|title=The Mulleins (Verbascum)|pages=p. 389| encyclopedia=Wild Flowers of the United States| volume=Volume 1. The Northeastern States (Part 2)| year=1966| editor=Harold William Rickett|location=New York| publisher=McGraw-Hill|id={{LCCN|66|0|17920}}}}</ref> In the 19th century it had well over 40 different common names in English alone. Some of the more whimsical ones included "Hig candlewick", "Bullicks lungwort", "Adams-rod", "Feltwort", "Hare's-beard" and "Ice-leaf".<ref>{{Cite encyclopedia| last=Britton| first=Nathaniel A.| coauthors=Addison Brown| encyclopedia=An illustrated flora of the northern United States and Canada |volume=V. 3. Gentianaceae to Compositae| year=1979| publisher=Dover Publications |location=New york| id=ISBN 0-486-22644-1| pages=p. 175}}</ref> Vernacular names include innumerable references to the plant's hairiness: "Woolly", "Velvet" or "Blanket Mullein",<ref name="elsevier633"/><ref>{{cite book| last=Brako| first=Lois| coauthors=Amy Y. Rossman and David F. Farr| title=  Scientific and common names of 7,000 vascular plants in the United States| year=1995|location=  St. Paul, Minnesota| publisher=APS Press| pages=p.189| isbn=0-89054-171-X}}</ref> "Beggar's", "Moses'", "Poor Man's", "Our Lady's" or "Old Man's Blanket",<ref name="grieve"/><ref name="Rickett"/><ref>Watts, ''Elsevier's dictionary of plant names'', pp.108, 369.</ref> and so on ("Flannel" is another common generic name).

Some names refer to the plant's size and shape: "Shepherd's Club(s)" or "Staff", "[[Aaron's Rod]]" (a name it shares with a number of other plants with tall, yellow inflorescences), and a plethora of other "X's Staff" and "X's Rod".<ref name="grieve"/><ref name="Rickett"/><ref>Watts, ''Elsevier's dictionary of plant names'', pp.774-775, 819-820. p.866: "A tall plant like Mullein attracts 'staff' and 'rod' names."</ref> The name "Velvet" or "Mullein Dock" is also recorded, where "dock" is a British name applied to any broad-leaved plant.<ref>Watts, ''Elsevier's dictionary of plant names'', pp.302, 634.</ref>

==Ecology==

[[Image:Starr 040723 0074 verbascum thapsus.jpg|thumb|right|''V. thapsus'' grows best where there is little competition]]
Great Mullein most frequently grows as a colonist of bare and disturbed soil, usually on sandy or chalky soils.<ref name="NWeurope"/> This is in part due to its intolerance of shade and the very long periods during which the seeds can remain dormant before [[germination]]. It is not an agricultural [[weed]], although its presence can be very difficult to completely eradicate, and is especially problematic in [[overgrazing|overgrazed]] pastures.<ref name="Hoshovsky">Hoshovsky (2001)</ref><ref name="davis">{{Cite web|last=Pitcairn|first=Michael|title=Verbascum thapsus |url=http://ucce.ucdavis.edu/datastore/detailreport.cfm?usernumber=87&surveynumber=182 |work=|publisher=[[University of California Davis]]|accessdate=2006-12-06}}</ref><ref name="remaley"/> The species is considered a [[noxious weed]] in [[Colorado]], [[United States]] (Class C),<ref>{{cite web|title=Colorado State-listed Noxious Weeds|url=http://plants.usda.gov/java/noxious?rptType=State&statefips=08| work=PLANTS Database| publisher=USDA Natural Resources Conservation Service| accessdate=2006-12-06}}</ref> Hawaii<ref>{{cite web|title=Hawaii State-listed Noxious Weeds|url=http://plants.usda.gov/java/noxious?rptType=State&statefips=15| work=PLANTS Database| publisher=USDA Natural Resources Conservation Service| accessdate=2006-12-06}}</ref> and [[Victoria, Australia]] (regionally prohibited in the [[West Gippsland]] region, and regionally controlled in several others).<ref>{{cite web|last=Faithful| first=Ian| title=Great Mullein| url=http://www.dpi.vic.gov.au/dpi/nreninf.nsf/LinkView/D2FE171D9ECA1CC9CA256BCF000AD563ECC844336D72F0634A256DEA00293F8A | publisher=Victoria Department of Primary Industries |accessdate=2006-12-06}}</ref>

It grows best in dry, sandy or gravelly soils, although it can grow in a variety of habitats, including banksides, meadows, roadsides, forest clearings and pastures. It germinates almost solely in bare soil, at temperatures between 10&nbsp;[[°C]] and 40&nbsp;°C.<ref name="Hoshovsky"/> This ability to grow in a wide range of habitats has been linked to strong [[phenotype]] variation rather than [[adaptation]] capacities.<ref>{{cite journal|last=Parker|first=Ingrid M.|coauthors=Joseph Rodriguez, Michael E. Loik| title=An Evolutionary Approach to Understanding the Biology of Invasions: Local Adaptation and General-Purpose Genotypes in the Weed Verbascum thapsus|journal=Conservation Biology|volume=17 |issue=1 |pages=59-72 |month=February |year=2003 |doi=10.1046/j.1523-1739.2003.02019.x}}</ref> While it can germinate in total darkness if proper conditions are present (tests give a 35% germination rate under ideal conditions), in the wild, it will only do so if the seeds are exposed, or very close to the soil surface. While it can also appear in areas where some vegetation exist, growth of the rosettes on bare soil is four to seven times more rapid.<ref name="Hoshovsky"/>

[[Megachilidae]] bees, notably ''[[Anthidium]]'' species, use the hair in making their [[nest]]s.<ref name="illinois">{{cite web|last=Hilty| first=John| title=Great Mullein|url=http://www.illinoiswildflowers.info/weeds/plants/great_mullein.htm|work= Weedy Wildflowers of Illinois|publisher=Illinois Wildflowers| accessdate=2006-12-06}}</ref> The seeds are generally too small for birds to feed on,<ref name="illinois"/> although the [[American Goldfinch]] has been reported to consume them.<ref>{{cite journal|last=Coutlee| first=Ellen L.| title=Maintenance Behavior of the American Goldfinch| url=http://elibrary.unm.edu/sora/Wilson/v075n04/p0342-p0357.pdf| journal=Wilson Bulletin| volume=75 |issue=4 |month=December |year=1963 |pages=342-357 |issn=0043-5643}}</ref> Other bird species have been reported to consume the leaves ([[Hawaiian Goose]])<ref>{{cite web|author=Banko ''et als''|title=Hawaiian Goose (Nene) (''Branta sandvicensis''): Food Habits| url=http://bna.birds.cornell.edu/BNA/account/Hawaiian_Goose/FOOD_HABITS.html |year=1999 |work=The Birds of North America, No. 434 |publisher=The Birds of North America Online |accessdate=2006-12-17}}</ref> or flowers ([[Palila]])<ref>{{cite web|author=Banko ''et als''|title=Palila (''Loxioides bailleui''): Food Habits |url=http://bna.birds.cornell.edu/BNA/account/Palila/FOOD_HABITS.html |year=2002 |work=The Birds of North America, No. 679 |publisher=The Birds of North America Online |accessdate=2006-12-17}}</ref> of ''V. thapsus'', or to use the plant as a source when [[foraging]] for insects ([[White-headed Woodpecker]]).<ref>{{cite web|author=Garrett ''et als''|title=White-headed Woodpecker (''Picoides albolarvatus''): Food Habits |url=http://bna.birds.cornell.edu/BNA/account/White-headed_Woodpecker/FOOD_HABITS.html |year=1996 |work=The Birds of North America, No. 252 |publisher=The Birds of North America Online|accessdate=2006-12-17}}</ref>

===Life cycle===

Great Mullein is a biennial and generally requires [[vernalization|winter dormancy]] before it can flower.<ref name="Hoshovsky"/> This dormancy is linked to [[starch]] degradation in the root activated by low temperatures, and [[gibberellin]] application bypasses this requirement.<ref name="phyt"/> Seeds germinate in spring and summer most often when exposed to light, those that germinate in autumn produce plants that overwinter if they are large enough with rosettes less than 15&nbsp;cm (5.9&nbsp;in) across dying in winter. After flowering the entire plant usually dies at the end of its second year<ref name="Hoshovsky"/> but some individuals, especially in the northern parts of the range, require a longer growth period and flower in their third year. Under longer growing conditions, some individuals flower in the first year.<ref>{{cite journal|last=Reinartz|first=James A.|title=Life History Variation of Common Mullein (''Verbascum Thapsus''): I. Latitudinal Differences in Population Dynamics and Timing of Reproduction|url= http://links.jstor.org/sici?sici=0022-0477%28198411%2972%3A3%3C897%3ALHVOCM%3E2.0.CO%3B2-N |journal=The Journal of Ecology |volume=72 |issue=3 |month=November |year=1984 |pages=897-912 |issn=0022-0477}}</ref> Triennial individuals were found to produce fewer seeds than biennial and annual ones. While year of flowering and size are linked to the environment, most other characteristics appear to be genetic.<ref>{{cite journal|last=Reinartz|first=James A.|title=Life History Variation of Common Mullein (''Verbascum Thapsus''): III. Differences Among Sequential Cohorts |url= http://links.jstor.org/sici?sici=0022-0477%28198411%2972%3A3%3C927%3ALHVOCM%3E2.0.CO%3B2-6 |journal=The Journal of Ecology |volume=72 |issue=3|month=November|year=1984|pages=927-936}}</ref>

A given flower is open only for a single day, opening before dawn and closing in the afternoon.<ref name="BoCW"/> Flowers are [[autogamy|autogamous]] and [[Dichogamy|protogynous]], with female parts maturating first,<ref name="BoCW"/> and will self-pollinate if they have not been [[pollination|pollinated]] by insects during the day. While many insects visit the flowers, only some bees actually accomplish pollination. ''V. thapsus''' flowering period lasts from June to August in most of its range, extending to September or October in warmer climates.<ref name="Hoshovsky"/><ref name="remaley"/><ref name="davis">Pitcairn</ref> Visitors include [[Halictidae|halictid]] bees and [[hoverfly|hoverflies]].<ref name="illinois">Hilty (2005)</ref> The hair on lower stamens may serve to provide footholds for visitors.<ref name="BoCW"/>

The seeds maintain their germinative powers for decades, up to a hundred years, according to some studies.<ref name="beal">{{Cite journal|last=Kivilaan| first=A.| coauthors=Robert S. Bandurski| title= The One Hundred-Year Period for Dr. Beal's Seed Viability Experiment|url= http://links.jstor.org/sici?sici=0002-9122%28198110%2968%3A9%3C1290%3ATOHPFD%3E2.0.CO%3B2-%23| journal=American Journal of Botany|volume=69| issue=9| month=October| year=1981| pages=1290-1292| issn=0002-9122}}</ref> Because of this, and because the plant is an extremely prolific seed bearer (each plant produces hundreds of capsules, each containing up to 700+ seeds,<ref name="BoCW"/> with a total up to 180,000<ref name="remaley"/><ref name="Hoshovsky"/> or 240,000<ref name="davis"/> seeds), it remains in the [[soil seed bank]] for extended periods of time, and can sprout from apparently bare ground,<ref name="Hoshovsky"/> or shortly after [[forest fire]]s long after previous plants have died.<ref name="davis"/> Its population pattern is typically an ephemeral adult population and long periods of dormancy as seeds.<ref name="BoCW"/> Great Mullein rarely establishes on new grounds without human intervention because its seeds are not dispersed very far. [[biological dispersal|Seed dispersion]] requires the stem to be moved by wind or animal movement; 75% of the seeds fall within 1 m of the parent plant, and 93% fall within 5 m.<ref name="Hoshovsky"/>

==Agricultural impacts and control==
Great Mullein is no longer considered a serious agricultural weed because it cannot compete with established plants, and is easily crowded out in cultivation,<ref name="BoCW">{{Cite journal| last=Gross| first=Katherine L.| coauthors=Patricia A. Werner| title=The Biology of Canadian Weeds. 28. ''Verbascum thapsus'' L. and ''V. blattaria'' L.| journal=Canadian Journal of Plant Science| volume=58| pages= 401-413| month=April| year=1978}} Reprinted in Mulligan, G.A. (1979), ''The Biology of Canadian Weeds'' I, ISBN 0-662-10668-7, pp. 320–331.</ref> except in areas where vegetation is sparse to begin with, such as [[California]]n semi-desertic areas of the Eastern [[Sierra Nevada (U.S.)|Sierra Nevada]]. In such ecological contexts, it crowds out native herbs and grasses. Its tendency to appear after [[forest fire]]s also disturbs the normal [[ecological succession]].<ref name="Hoshovsky"/><ref name="davis"/> In the past, when fields were hand cultivated, it was a serious pest species and called a troublesome weed. 

Despite not being an agricultural weed in itself, it [[Host (biology)|hosts]] a number of insects and [[disease]]s, including both [[pest (organism)|pest]]s and [[beneficial insects]].<ref name="horton">{{cite journal |last= Horton|first= David R.|coauthors= Tamera M. Lewis|year= 2003|month= December|title= Numbers and types of arthropods overwintering on common mullein, Verbascum thapsus L. (Scrophulariaceae), in a central Washington fruit-growing region|journal= Journal of the Entomological Society of British Columbia|volume= 100|issue= |pages= 79-86|issn=0071-0733|url= http://www.sfu.ca/biology/esbc/Journal/journal2003/2003_Horton.pdf |accessdate=2007-08-19}}</ref> It is also a potential reservoir of the [[cucumber mosaic virus]], [[powdery mildew]] (''Erysiphum cichoraceum'') and [[Texas root rot]].<ref name="BoCW"/><ref>{{cite journal| last=Price| first=W. C.| title=Comparative Host Ranges of Six Plant Viruses|url=http://links.jstor.org/sici?sici=0002-9122(194007)27:7%3C530:CHROSP%3E2.0.CO;2-5| journal=American Journal of Botany|month=July|year=1940|volume=57|issue=7|pages=530-541|issn=00029122}}</ref> A study found ''V. thapsus'' hosts insects from 29 different [[family (biology)|families]]. Most of the pests found were [[western flower thrips]] (''Frankliniella occidentalis''), ''[[Lygus]]'' species such as the [[tarnished plant bug]] (''L. lineolaris''), and various [[spider mite]]s from the family [[Tetranychidae]]. These make the plant a potential reservoir for [[overwintering]] pests.<ref name="horton"/>

Other insects commonly found on Great Mullein feed exclusively on ''Verbascum'' species in general or ''V. thapsus'' in particular. They include mullein thrips (''[[Haplothrips]] verbasci''),<ref name="horton"/> ''[[Gymnaetron tetrum]]'' and the [[Mullein Moth]] (''Cucullia verbasci'').<ref name="remaley"/> Useful insects are also hosted by Great Mullein, including predatory mites of the ''Galendromus'', ''Typhlodromus'' and ''Amblyseius'' [[genus|genera]] ([[Phytoseiidae]]), the [[minute pirate bug]] (''Orius tristicolor'')<ref name="horton"/> and the [[mullein plant bug]] (''Campylomma verbasci'').<ref name="bradley">{{cite web|last=Higbee|first=Bradley S.|title=Campylomma verbasci (Meyer)|url=http://www.nysaes.cornell.edu/ent/biocontrol/predators/c_verbasci.html| work=Biological Control: A Guide to Natural Enemies in North America| publisher=[[Cornell University]]|accessdate=2006-12-06}}</ref> The plant's ability to host both pests and beneficials makes it potentially useful to maintain stable populations of insects used for biological control in other cultures, like ''Campylomma verbasci'' and ''Dicyphus hesperus'' ([[Miridae]]), a predator of [[whitefly|whiteflies]].<ref>{{cite journal|last=Sanchez|first=Juan Antonio|coauthors=David R. Gillespie, Robert R. McGregor|title=The effects of mullein plants (''Verbascum thapsus'') on the population dynamics of ''Dicyphus hesperus'' (Heteroptera: Miridae) in tomato greenhouses|journal=Biological Control|volme=28|issue=3|month=November|year=2003|pages=313-319| doi=10.1016/S1049-9644(03)00116-6}}</ref> A number of pest [[Lepidoptera]] species, including the [[Stalk Borer]] (''Papaipema nebris'') and [[Gray Hairstreak]] (''Strymon melinus''), also use ''V. thapsus'' as a host plant.<ref>{{cite web|title=HOSTS - a Database of the World's Lepidopteran Hostplants|url= http://avalanche.nhm.ac.uk/jdsml/research-curation/projects/hostplants//list.dsml?searchPageURL=index.dsml&Familyqtype=starts+with&Family=&PFamilyqtype=starts+with&PFamily=&Genusqtype=starts+with&Genus=&PGenusqtype=starts+with&PGenus=verbascum&Speciesqtype=starts+with&PSpeciesqtype=starts+with&PSpecies=thapsus&sort=Family |publisher=The [[Natural History Museum]]|accessdate=2006-12-17}}</ref>

[[Image:Common Mullein closeup.jpg|right|thumb|The hairy leaves are resistant to grazing and contact herbicides.]]

Control of the plant, when desired, is best managed via mechanical means, such as hand pulling and hoeing, preferably followed by sowing of native plants. Animals rarely [[grazing|graze]] it because of its irritating hairs, and liquid [[herbicide]]s require [[surfactant]]s to be effective, as the hair causes water to roll off the plant, much like the [[lotus effect]]. Burning is ineffective, as it only creates new bare areas for [[seedling]]s to occupy.<ref name="Hoshovsky"/><ref name="davis"/><ref name="remaley"/> ''G. tetrum'' and ''Cucullia verbasci'' usually have little effect on ''V. thapsus'' populations.<ref name="remaley"/> Goats and chickens have been proposed to control Mullein.<ref name="Hoshovsky"/> Effective (when used with a surfactant) contact herbicides include [[glyphosate]],<ref name="remaley"/><ref name="davis"/> [[triclopyr]]<ref name="remaley"/> and [[sulfurometuron-methyl]].<ref name="davis"/> Ground herbicides, like [[tebuthiuron]], are also effective, but recreate bare ground and require repeated application to prevent regrowth.<ref name="Hoshovsky"/>

==Uses==
Great Mullein has been used since ancient times as a remedy for skin, throat and breathing ailments. It has long had a medicinal reputation, especially as an [[astringent]] and [[emollient]]. It contains [[mucilage]], several [[saponin]]s, [[coumarin]] and [[glycoside]]s. [[Dioscorides]] recommended it for diseases of the [[lung]] and it is nowadays widely available in health and herbal stores. Non-medical uses have included [[dye]]ing and making [[torch]]es.

===Medical uses===
[[Pedanius Dioscorides|Dioscorides]] first recommended the plant 2000 years ago, against pulmonary diseases,<ref name="silverman">{{cite book |last=Silverman |first= Maida| year=1977| title=A City Herbal: Lore, Legend, & Uses of Common Weeds| chapter=Mullein| chapterurl=http://www.ashtreepublishing.com/Book_City_Herbal_Mullen.htm |pages=99-104|isbn= 1-888123-00-1}}</ref> and this has remained one of its primary uses, especially against [[cough]]. Leaf [[decoction]]s or [[herbal tea]]s were used for [[expectoration]], consumption, dry cough, [[bronchitis]], sore throat and [[hemorrhoid]]s. Leaves were also smoked against pulmonary ailments, a tradition that in America was rapidly transmitted to [[Native Americans in the United States|Native American]]  peoples.<ref name="grieve">{{cite encyclopedia|last=Grieve|first=Margaret|encyclopedia=A Modern Herbal|title=Mullein, Great|origyear=1931|year=1982|url=http://botanical.com/botanical/mgmh/m/mulgre63.html |accessdate=2006-11-29| location=New York |publisher=Dover Publication|volume= Volume 2: I-Z |id= ISBN 0-486-22799-5}}</ref><ref name="hanrahan">{{cite encyclopedia | last = Hanrahan | first = Claire | coauthors = Rebecca J. Frey | editor = Jacqueline L. Longe | encyclopedia = The Gale encyclopedia of alternative medicine | title = Mullein | url = http://health.enotes.com/alternative-medicine-encyclopedia/mullein | accessdate = 2006-11-30 | edition = 2nd edition | year = 2005 | publisher = Thomson Gale | volume = Volume 3: L-R | location = Detroit | id = ISBN 0-7876-7427-3}}</ref> They used the non-indigenous plant to make syrups against croup. The combination of [[expectorant]] saponins and emollient mucilage makes the plant particularly effective for cough. All preparations meant to be drunk have to be finely filtered to eliminate the irritating hairs.<ref name="phyt">{{Cite journal| last=Turker|first=Arzu Ucar |coauthors= Ekrem Gurel|title=Common Mullein (''Verbascum thapsus'' L.): Recent Advances in Research|journal=Phytotherapy Research |volume=19| issue=9| month=September| year=2005 |pages=733–739|doi=10.1002/ptr.1653}}</ref>

Oil from the flowers was used against [[catarrh]]s, [[colic]]s and, in [[Germany]], [[earache]]s, [[frostbite]], [[eczema]] and other external conditions.<ref name="grieve"/> Topical application of various ''V. thapsus''-based preparations was recommended for the treatment of [[wart]]s,<ref>{{cite journal|last=Drury|first=Susan| title=Plants and Wart Cures in England from the Seventeenth to the Nineteenth Century: Some Examples| url=http://links.jstor.org/sici?sici=0015-587X(1991)102%3A1%3C97%3APAWCIE%3E2.0.CO%3B2-X |journal=Folklore| volume=102| issue=1| year=1991| pages=97-100|issn=0015-587X}}</ref> [[boil]]s, [[carbuncle]]s, [[hemorrhoid]]s, and [[chilblain]]s, amongst others.<ref name="grieve"/><Ref name="hanrahan"/> Recent studies have found that Great Mullein contains [[glycyrrhizin]] compounds with [[bactericide]] and potential anti-[[tumor]]al action. These compounds are concentrated in the flowers.<ref>{{cite journal| last=Turker|first=Arzu Ucar |coauthors= N. D. Camper| title=Biological activity of common mullein, a medicinal plant|journal= Journal of Ethnopharmacology |month=October|year=2002| volume=82| issue=2-3| pages=117-125 | doi=10.1016/S0378-8741(02)00186-1}}</ref> Different extracts have varying levels of efficiency against bacterias.<ref name="phyt"/> In Germany, a governmental commission sanctioned medicinal use of the plant for catarrhs.<ref>{{cite web|title=Mullein flower|url=http://www.herbalgram.org/iherb/commissione/Monographs/Monograph_0262.html |work= The Commission E Monographs| date=[[February 1]], [[1990]]|publisher=American Botanical Council|accessdate=2006-12-06}}</ref> It was also part of the [[National Formulary]] in the United States<ref name="hanrahan"/> and United Kingdom.<ref name="grieve"/> The plant's leaves, in addition to the seeds, have been reported to contain [[rotenone]], although quantities are unknown.<ref name="pfaf">{{cite web|title=Verbascum thapsus| url=http://www.pfaf.org/database/plants.php?Verbascum+thapsus |publisher=Plants For A Future |accessdate= 2006-12-06}}</ref>

In [[Spanish language|Spanish]], Great Mullein is called ''Gordolobo''. ''[[Gnaphalium]] conoideum'' was used in a fashion similar to Mullein by the [[Mexico|Mexican]] [[Aztec]]s, which caused confusion in naming, and both are sold under the name "Gordolobo", (although ''V. thapsus'' is not found in Mexico). This situation has led to at least one case of poisoning due to confusion of ''G. conoideum'' with ''[[Senecio]] longilobus.''<ref>{{cite journal|last=Kay| first=Margaret| title=Poisoning by Gordolobo|url=http://www.herbalgram.org/iherb/herbalgram/articleview.asp?a=1122 |journal=HerbalGram|issue=32|pages=42|year=1994|month=Fall| issn=0899-5648}}</ref>

===Other uses===
Like many ancient medicinal plants ([[Pliny the Elder]] describes it in his ''[[Natural History (Pliny)|Naturalis Historia]]''),{{ref label|Pliny|D|}} Great Mullein was linked to [[witch]]es,<ref name="grieve"/> although the relationship remained generally ambiguous, and the plant was also widely held to ward off [[curse]]s and [[evil spirit]]s.<ref name="grieve"/><ref name="phyt"/><ref name="silverman"/><ref name="hanrahan"/> The seeds contain several compounds (saponins, glycosides, coumarin, rotenone) that cause breathing problems in fish, and have been widely used as [[piscicide]] for [[fishing]].<ref name="remaley"/><ref>{{Cite journal|last=Wilhelm| first=Gene| title=The mullein: Plant piscicide of the mountain folk culture| journal=Geographic Review| volume=64| issue=2| pages=235-252|month=April| year=1974| doi=10.2307/213812}}</ref>

The flowers provide dyes of bright yellow or green, and have been used for [[hair dye]].<ref name="grieve"/><ref name="pfaf"/> The dried leaves and hair were made into [[candle wick]]s, or put into shoes to help with insulating them. The dried stems were also dipped into [[suet]] or [[wax]] to make torches.<ref name="grieve"/><ref name="hanrahan"/> For obvious reasons, the plant, unlike other species of the genus, is not often cultivated.

